value.title: 'CyberVolk' ransomware was detected
value.description:
Ransomware use common methods to encrypt files using keys that are known only to attackers. As a result, victims are unable to access the contents of the encrypted files. Most ransomware display or drop a ransom note—an image or an HTML file that contains information about how to obtain the attacker-supplied decryption tool for a fee.   

To target documents or other files that contain user data, some ransomware look for files in certain locations and files with certain extension names. It is also common for ransomware to rename encrypted files so that they all use the same extension name.  

This detection might indicate that the malware was stopped from delivering its payload. However, it is prudent to check the machine for signs of infection.

For more information, read the Ransomware: A pervasive and ongoing threat Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/05658b6c-dc62-496d-ad3c-c6a795a33c27/analystreport

value.title: Ransomware-linked Sangria Tempest threat activity group detected
value.description:
Sangria Tempest is also known as FIN7 (FireEye) and Carbon Spider (CrowdStrike). The group is also at times equated to Carbanak Group/Gang (MITRE); JokerStash (Gemini Advisory); Navigator Group (US Department of Justice) but so far, this attribution is seen to be inconsistent and is provided for situational awareness.

Sangria Tempest is a sophisticated activity group, suspected to be of Eastern European origins, that has been known to be in operation since 2012 and that runs multiple campaigns targeting a broad set of industries for financial gain. Back in 2018, this group made headlines when three of its members were arrested. In May 2020, another arrest was made for an individual with alleged involvement with Sangria Tempest. However, even after the arrests, Microsoft has observed sustained campaigns from the group itself and it is considered largely active.

The group has been confused with another group called Carbanak, also known as Cobalt Spider (CrowdStrike), as both groups have been observed to have used the Carbanak backdoor implant in their operations, as well as used the same supply chain channels and underground vendors in the Dark Web, in monetizing their activities for instance. While Carbanak (the group) is involved with large-scale online banking theft via targeted attacks against end customers of various financial institutions, Sangria Tempest targets point-of-sale (PoS) systems, and more recently, on cryptocurrency platforms. Sangria Tempest has also been seen to have used a front security company called _Combi Security_.

Sangria Tempest employs sophisticated social engineering and evasion techniques to gain access to targets and maintain persistence. The group has deployed point-of-sale (PoS) malware and ATM malware to collect payment card information from in-store checkout terminals. They have also targeted corporate personnel who have access sensitive financial data, including individuals involved in SEC filings. 

Sangria Tempest has demonstrated a shift away from PoS malware to a preference for deploying ransomware and double extortion of victims via data theft. The group has used multiple ransomware families, including MAZE in mid-2020, and DarkSide since it was released in late 2020.

For more information, read:
- Actor profile: Sangria Tempest Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/77c60fe4-03a8-4e81-ac29-bdc2ab14d40e/analystreport

- Activity profile: Financially motivated threat actors misusing App Installer Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/578d22a8-f385-4639-8309-e39eff88345e/analystreport?

value.title: A file or network connection related to a ransomware-linked emerging threat activity group detected
value.description:
A file creation or network connection event contained a suspicious indicator related to Storm-0300. Examples of these indicators can include file hashes, domain names, or behaviors. Please consider the mitigation recommendations in the context of the event that triggered the detection. 

The group Microsoft tracks as Storm-0300 represents unattributed activity associated with ransomware attacks, including both pre-ransomware activities and ransomware deployment. As multiple cybercrime actors customize and reuse a range of common tools and techniques deployed in ransomware attacks and the relationships between actors change very rapidly, Microsoft labels observed ransomware-related activity that has not yet been associated with a known tracked group as Storm-0300. As more patterns are identified from this activity, it is often merged into existing Activity Groups or split into new, well-defined clusters.

Storm-0300 techniques include, but are not limited to, phishing, compromised credentials, vulnerability exploitation to obtain initial access, installing malware or backdoors for lateral movement, persistence, data exfiltration, as well as post-exploitation tools such as Cobalt Strike. These techniques can further facilitate deployment of various ransomware payloads. Additionally, in their attacks, threat actors might tweak their techniques and use tools to evade and turn off security products. They are also well-versed in system administration and try to blend in as much as possible.

For more information, read the Storm-0300 ransomware activity Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/1f4ce9ac-779e-46ea-9445-e9b02c087770/analystreport?

value.title: A file or network connection related to a ransomware-linked emerging threat activity group detected
value.description:
A file creation or network connection event contained a suspicious indicator related to Storm-0300. Examples of these indicators can include file hashes, domain names, or behaviors. Please consider the mitigation recommendations in the context of the event that triggered the detection. 

The group Microsoft tracks as Storm-0300 represents unattributed activity associated with ransomware attacks, including both pre-ransomware activities and ransomware deployment. As multiple cybercrime actors customize and reuse a range of common tools and techniques deployed in ransomware attacks and the relationships between actors change very rapidly, Microsoft labels observed ransomware-related activity that has not yet been associated with a known tracked group as Storm-0300. As more patterns are identified from this activity, it is often merged into existing Activity Groups or split into new, well-defined clusters.

Storm-0300 techniques include, but are not limited to, phishing, compromised credentials, vulnerability exploitation to obtain initial access, installing malware or backdoors for lateral movement, persistence, data exfiltration, as well as post-exploitation tools such as Cobalt Strike. These techniques can further facilitate deployment of various ransomware payloads. Additionally, in their attacks, threat actors might tweak their techniques and use tools to evade and turn off security products. They are also well-versed in system administration and try to blend in as much as possible.

For more information, read the Storm-0300 ransomware activity Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/1f4ce9ac-779e-46ea-9445-e9b02c087770/analystreport?

value.title: 'Phobos' ransomware was detected
value.description:
Ransomware use common methods to encrypt files using keys that are known only to attackers. As a result, victims are unable to access the contents of the encrypted files. Most ransomware display or drop a ransom note—an image or an HTML file that contains information about how to obtain the attacker-supplied decryption tool for a fee.   

To target documents or other files that contain user data, some ransomware look for files in certain locations and files with certain extension names. It is also common for ransomware to rename encrypted files so that they all use the same extension name.  

This detection might indicate that the malware was stopped from delivering its payload. However, it is prudent to check the machine for signs of infection.

For more information, read the Ransomware: A pervasive and ongoing threat Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/05658b6c-dc62-496d-ad3c-c6a795a33c27/analystreport

value.title: Ransomware-linked Sangria Tempest threat activity group detected
value.description:
Sangria Tempest is also known as FIN7 (FireEye) and Carbon Spider (CrowdStrike). The group is also at times equated to Carbanak Group/Gang (MITRE); JokerStash (Gemini Advisory); Navigator Group (US Department of Justice) but so far, this attribution is seen to be inconsistent and is provided for situational awareness.

Sangria Tempest is a sophisticated activity group, suspected to be of Eastern European origins, that has been known to be in operation since 2012 and that runs multiple campaigns targeting a broad set of industries for financial gain. Back in 2018, this group made headlines when three of its members were arrested. In May 2020, another arrest was made for an individual with alleged involvement with Sangria Tempest. However, even after the arrests, Microsoft has observed sustained campaigns from the group itself and it is considered largely active.

The group has been confused with another group called Carbanak, also known as Cobalt Spider (CrowdStrike), as both groups have been observed to have used the Carbanak backdoor implant in their operations, as well as used the same supply chain channels and underground vendors in the Dark Web, in monetizing their activities for instance. While Carbanak (the group) is involved with large-scale online banking theft via targeted attacks against end customers of various financial institutions, Sangria Tempest targets point-of-sale (PoS) systems, and more recently, on cryptocurrency platforms. Sangria Tempest has also been seen to have used a front security company called _Combi Security_.

Sangria Tempest employs sophisticated social engineering and evasion techniques to gain access to targets and maintain persistence. The group has deployed point-of-sale (PoS) malware and ATM malware to collect payment card information from in-store checkout terminals. They have also targeted corporate personnel who have access sensitive financial data, including individuals involved in SEC filings. 

Sangria Tempest has demonstrated a shift away from PoS malware to a preference for deploying ransomware and double extortion of victims via data theft. The group has used multiple ransomware families, including MAZE in mid-2020, and DarkSide since it was released in late 2020.

For more information, read:
- Actor profile: Sangria Tempest Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/77c60fe4-03a8-4e81-ac29-bdc2ab14d40e/analystreport

- Activity profile: Financially motivated threat actors misusing App Installer Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/578d22a8-f385-4639-8309-e39eff88345e/analystreport?

As more patterns are identified from this activity, it is often merged into existing Activity Groups or split into new, well-defined clusters.

Storm-0300 techniques include, but are not limited to, phishing, compromised credentials, vulnerability exploitation to obtain initial access, installing malware or backdoors for lateral movement, persistence, data exfiltration, as well as post-exploitation tools such as Cobalt Strike. These techniques can further facilitate deployment of various ransomware payloads. Additionally, in their attacks, threat actors might tweak their techniques and use tools to evade and turn off security products. They are also well-versed in system administration and try to blend in as much as possible.

For more information, read the Storm-0300 ransomware activity Threat Analytics report: https://security.microsoft.com/threatanalytics3/1f4ce9ac-779e-46ea-9445-e9b02c087770/analystreport?
